Pages = {247-263},
Note = {6th International Conference on the Ecology and Management of Alien
   Plant Invasions, UNIV LOUGHBOROUGH, LOUGHBOROUGH, ENGLAND, SEP, 2001},
Abstract = {The invasion by Carpobrotus edulis (L.) N.E. Br. and C affine
   acinaciformis (L.) L. Bol. along the Provencal coastline of France
   provides a unique opportunity to enrich our understanding of the effects
   of insularity (i.e. island vs mainland habitats) on the reproductive
   systems of invasive taxa. C. edulis vegetative growth is habitat
   dependent with highest performances in insular sand dunes. Pollen
   dispersal distances for C. edulis are higher in island populations as
   compared to the mainland. For C. affine acinaciformis, a paucity of
   pollen dispersal events also indicated poor pollinator service on the
   mainland. C. edulis has signficantly higher manual selfing fruit
   maturation and spontaneous selfing mean seed counts on Bagaud island as
   compared to the mainland, but has significantly higher agamospermy seed
   counts on the mainland as compared to Bagaud island. C. affine
   acinaciformis has significantly higher performance in its mainland as
   compared to its island population for spontaneous selfing, manual
   selfing, and manual outcrossing fruit maturation, as well as spontaneous
   selfing, manual outcrossing and free pollination mean seed counts. C.
   affine acinaciformis fruit maturation in hybridisation was significantly
   higher on the island of Bagaud than on the mainland. This is most likely
   from the hybridisation histories of C. affine acinaciformis populations,
   and not indicative of the presence or absence of an island specific
   pattern among the reproductive alternatives of different taxa. Due to
   the importance of habitat, pollinator services and differences in
   taxonomic status demonstrated by this study, invasions should be
   approached on a case-by-case basis. Knowledge of the invasion history
   and genetics of the populations being studied is necessary for sound
   conclusions, and more importance should be given to the role of
   mutualisms in invasion ecology.},
